<div class="historical-section" id="historical-trend">
  <h2>Historical Trend: A Decade of Dropping Fees</h2>
  <p>Over the past decade, the asset management industry has experienced massive fee compression. The average expense ratio for an equity mutual fund in 2000 was nearly <strong>1.00%</strong>. By 2010, the proliferation of ETFs pushed that average closer to <strong>0.70%</strong>.</p>
  <p>Today, as our 2026 analysis shows, the overall ETF average has fallen to <strong>0.164%</strong>, largely driven by the explosive growth of passive index funds which now routinely charge less than 0.05%. This "race to zero" has saved retail investors <strong>billions of dollars</strong> in aggregate, forcing even active managers to justify their fees with clear outperformance or highly specialized strategies.</p>
  <p>The fee war is far from over. Fidelity launched zero-fee index mutual funds in 2018, and multiple issuers continue to trim expense ratios annually. For investors, this is unambiguously good news — every basis point saved compounds to real wealth over decades.</p>
</div>

